    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-11-17T12:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-11-17T12:00:00-05:00" n="1091"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1091">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">711.94114A/11–1744: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Switzerland</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Harrison</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Bern</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-11-17T18:00:00+01:00"
                            >November 17, 1944—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 10:12 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>7605. American Interests—Far East. Foreign Office note November 14 states Swiss
                    Legation, Tokyo, accords financial assistance to all American prisoners of war
                    and internees in Far East as requested Department’s 3183, September 14, and in
                    accordance with procedure adopted in transmitting funds to American civilian
                    internees Philippines. Japanese Foreign Office asked Swiss Legation establish
                    assistance plan on basis of lists furnished by Japanese Prisoners of War
                    Information Bureau. These lists reveal 1013 prisoners of war Fukuoka, 89
                    Hakodate, 1974 Osaka, 1344 Tokyo, 980 Mukden, 257 Formosa, <pb facs="1083"
                        n="1071" xml:id="pg_1071"/> 196 Thailand, 6 Malaya and 36 civilians reported
                    Singapore and 6 Burma.</p>
                <p>Swiss Legation proposes fix relief at 15 yen monthly per person and it will
                    insist that it be used preferably for collective purchases in accordance with
                    Department’s 2860, August 19. Should 15 yen per person appear too much view lack
                    purchaseable articles, Swiss Legation envisages reductions down to 5 yen
                    monthly.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Harrison</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
